      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Modern historians largely view the UN as a mixed success that has shifted from preventing major interstate wars to managing internal conflicts and humanitarian crises. While the UN successfully prevented a third world war since 1945, its ability to stop large-scale civil wars or regional conflicts in the 21st century has been severely limited by the veto power of the five permanent Security Council members. Consequently, most scholars argue that the UN is effective at diplomacy and peacekeeping when the UN is willing to act, but fundamentally fails to stop big wars when the major powers are united against its authority.",
